WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.160
Today, I'd like to talk about democratizing R using the Plumber package.

00:00:13.160 --> 00:00:18.160
And so to get started, what I want to do is kind of go through and provide an introduction

00:00:18.160 --> 00:00:22.559
to Plumber if you are perhaps unfamiliar with the package or haven't been exposed to it

00:00:22.559 --> 00:00:23.559
before.

00:00:23.559 --> 00:00:27.820
And then highlight some new features that we have that allow us to integrate more tightly

00:00:27.820 --> 00:00:30.379
with OpenAPI, things of that nature.

00:00:30.379 --> 00:00:35.500
And then finally, walk through a use case, maybe typical example use case of what Plumber

00:00:35.500 --> 00:00:37.540
could be used for.

00:00:37.540 --> 00:00:42.180
And then walk through a demonstration of what that might look like.

00:00:42.180 --> 00:00:48.540
So if you're unfamiliar, Plumber is an R package that allows you to create API endpoints around

00:00:48.540 --> 00:00:49.540
common R functions.

00:00:49.540 --> 00:00:53.500
So you can define any sort of R function that you're interested in, and then with a few

00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:57.380
simple commands, you can turn that R function into an endpoint that can then be interacted

00:00:57.939 --> 00:01:00.700
with via any sort of API call.

00:01:00.700 --> 00:01:04.500
This looks like an example Plumber script would look something like this.

00:01:04.500 --> 00:01:08.339
And again, if you haven't been exposed to Plumber before, there may be some pieces in

00:01:08.339 --> 00:01:10.699
here that aren't quite recognizable.

00:01:10.699 --> 00:01:14.300
But for the most part, if we kind of abstract away the specific Plumber parts for just a

00:01:14.300 --> 00:01:18.779
moment, this starts to look like just a typical R script, right?

00:01:18.779 --> 00:01:20.779
At the top here, I load the Plumber package.

00:01:20.779 --> 00:01:23.059
I load in some saved data object that I have.

00:01:23.059 --> 00:01:25.980
And I apologize if this is a little small in the back.

00:01:25.980 --> 00:01:28.860
This is all available on GitHub, and I'll make sure that you have the link to review

00:01:28.860 --> 00:01:29.940
this later.

00:01:29.940 --> 00:01:34.099
But then I load some saved data object, and then finally, I define a function that interacts

00:01:34.099 --> 00:01:35.099
with that object.

00:01:35.099 --> 00:01:38.620
We'll dive into this function perhaps a little bit later in our demonstration.

00:01:38.620 --> 00:01:43.980
But in essence, this looks and feels like R code because it is.

00:01:43.980 --> 00:01:48.419
To look at the Plumber specific pieces as we walk through this, Plumber uses specialized

00:01:48.419 --> 00:01:53.620
annotations, and these are just special comments written in the regular comment syntax in R

00:01:53.779 --> 00:01:57.220
with the hash symbol, and then that's followed by a little asterisk.

00:01:57.220 --> 00:02:00.580
And this allows us to annotate our document or our source script in a way that Plumber

00:02:00.580 --> 00:02:06.099
can then understand and interpret our just standard R code and turn it into these APIs.

00:02:06.099 --> 00:02:11.820
So here, this initial, these few initial comments here provide an API name and description from

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:12.820
an API.

00:02:12.820 --> 00:02:16.779
So I'm calling this the empty cars model API, and I provide a little description about what's

00:02:16.779 --> 00:02:18.539
going to happen.

00:02:18.539 --> 00:02:23.220
The next step that I have is I have this filter that's defined, and a filter is used when

00:02:23.820 --> 00:02:28.740
I have some sort of logic that I want to take place on an incoming request before it's served

00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:29.779
to an endpoint.

00:02:29.779 --> 00:02:33.500
And so this is where I could do something like if I want to provide some sort of authentication

00:02:33.500 --> 00:02:36.460
on incoming requests, I could use a filter to do that.

00:02:36.460 --> 00:02:40.580
Here this example filter simply takes some information from the incoming request, such

00:02:40.580 --> 00:02:45.220
as where this is coming from, the user ID associated with it, a timestamp, and prints

00:02:45.220 --> 00:02:50.179
that out so that I have a nice log available to me of who's interacting with my API as

00:02:50.179 --> 00:02:53.059
well as the frequency that this API is being interacted with.

00:02:53.059 --> 00:02:59.220
So any time a request is made, this information would be printed out and I could capture that.

00:02:59.220 --> 00:03:03.539
Finally we have the function that I started with when we demonstrated this R code, and

00:03:03.539 --> 00:03:07.179
I just have a few different things that I have that I've annotated on this function.

00:03:07.179 --> 00:03:11.380
I've given it a name and a little description, and then I've defined the endpoint that this

00:03:11.380 --> 00:03:12.740
function should respond to.

00:03:12.740 --> 00:03:17.119
So again, I apologize if it's a little small, but I've defined that this function will respond

00:03:17.119 --> 00:03:25.320
or will be called when the predict endpoint is accessed with a post request.

00:03:25.320 --> 00:03:28.440
To go a little bit further, once I have all these annotations in place and I actually

00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:32.720
run this API, this thing on the right-hand side gets generated for me.

00:03:32.720 --> 00:03:37.399
And as an R user when I was first exposed to Plumber, this was like a mind-blowing moment

00:03:37.399 --> 00:03:40.880
because I wasn't overly familiar with APIs.

00:03:40.880 --> 00:03:43.119
They seemed kind of scary to me as an R user for a little while.

00:03:43.119 --> 00:03:46.559
It's like this thing that everybody knows about, I don't know what it is, right?

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:53.399
But I started using Plumber, and as soon as I ran my API, all of a sudden, free of charge,

00:03:53.399 --> 00:03:57.479
I have this nice little interface that would pop up and not only show me what my API looks

00:03:57.479 --> 00:04:01.039
like, but it allows me to touch and feel the API to make sure that it's operating as I

00:04:01.039 --> 00:04:02.399
would expect.

00:04:02.399 --> 00:04:06.279
If we look at a comparison between the code that we've written and this file and user

00:04:06.279 --> 00:04:10.279
interface that's been generated, we can start to see how these two things are connected.

00:04:10.279 --> 00:04:15.759
Here I see that my title has been copied from my source code into this user interface.

00:04:15.759 --> 00:04:20.519
I can see that the description matches the description that I defined in my R script.

00:04:20.519 --> 00:04:24.799
And finally, I have this endpoint that's been defined, this predict endpoint that shows

00:04:24.799 --> 00:04:29.519
that it's going to respond to post requests, and it shows the description that I provided

00:04:29.519 --> 00:04:32.480
in my source code.

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:36.480
This sort of magical experience is made possible through the use of OpenAPI.

00:04:36.480 --> 00:04:39.359
Now what OpenAPI is, it was formerly referred to as Swagger.

00:04:39.359 --> 00:04:43.480
This is a specification, so it's a set of guidelines that defines a way that you can

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:47.600
go through and essentially describe an entire API.

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:51.640
The endpoints, the attributes of those endpoints, everything from kind of the top to bottom

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:55.920
of your API can be described using this particular specification.

00:04:55.920 --> 00:04:57.420
There's a few different ways this can happen.

00:04:57.420 --> 00:05:00.920
You can write like a YAML file, which is the example that I have pulled up on the screen.

00:05:00.920 --> 00:05:06.059
You can also create a JSON file that is then ingested and interpreted by OpenAPI to provide

00:05:06.059 --> 00:05:11.000
things like the user interface we were just looking at.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.519
Plumber interacts with OpenAPI in a couple of different ways.

00:05:13.519 --> 00:05:16.959
We've already been exposed to one, and that is through these specialized comments where

00:05:16.959 --> 00:05:20.440
we have the hash symbol followed by an asterisk, and then typically some sort of decorator

00:05:20.440 --> 00:05:21.839
like an at symbol.

00:05:21.839 --> 00:05:26.200
And what happens is Plumber will parse the file, identify these special comments, and

00:05:26.200 --> 00:05:31.720
then insert those into a named list that is finally processed into a JSON file that OpenAPI

00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:34.399
will read and provide us with the user interface.

00:05:34.399 --> 00:05:38.000
Now this functionality has been in Plumber since essentially day one.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:43.880
And one of the nice advantages here is that my annotations, my documentation, my description

00:05:43.880 --> 00:05:46.119
is all closely connected to my code.

00:05:46.119 --> 00:05:47.519
They're right next to one another.

00:05:47.519 --> 00:05:52.320
However, there are some limitations here, and that is the entire suite of options that

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:56.480
are available through OpenAPI is very broad, right?

00:05:56.480 --> 00:06:00.959
And so it's not feasible to consider creating a specialized Plumber annotation that provides

00:06:00.959 --> 00:06:06.160
access to every single feature available using the OpenAPI specification.

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:08.959
And I'm happy to announce that given some recent efforts that have happened with the

00:06:08.959 --> 00:06:15.440
Plumber package, we now have the opportunity to update and adjust the full OpenAPI specification

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:18.040
at runtime of the Plumber API.

00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:23.079
What this looks like is over here on the right-hand side, I have an entry point file that Plumber

00:06:23.079 --> 00:06:29.040
will read, and in this entry point file, I define at runtime a swagger function that

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:33.559
essentially will take in a few different arguments, and all it needs to return is a named list

00:06:33.559 --> 00:06:37.839
that can be appropriately parsed into JSON that OpenAPI can interpret.

00:06:37.839 --> 00:06:42.359
So I can update anything that I've written, or I can add additional attributes to my API.

00:06:42.359 --> 00:06:46.079
In fact, if I wanted to, I could overwrite everything that Plumber has already automatically

00:06:46.079 --> 00:06:50.579
done and just create my own specification file for my API to be ingested and then rendered

00:06:50.579 --> 00:06:53.880
for the end user.

00:06:53.880 --> 00:06:56.959
Given this introduction, let's consider an example use case.

00:06:56.959 --> 00:07:01.279
As a data scientist, I'm often handed a piece of data and asked to provide some insight,

00:07:01.279 --> 00:07:04.079
and I go through this process that's described in R for Data Science.

00:07:04.079 --> 00:07:08.399
I ingest the data, I do some cleaning of my data, and then finally I go through this iterative

00:07:08.399 --> 00:07:12.739
process of trying to understand the story or understand the insight that should be delivered

00:07:12.739 --> 00:07:15.200
from my data.

00:07:15.200 --> 00:07:19.200
Being a data scientist, that means I'm often creating models, and so I'm going to dig deep

00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:22.279
into my bag of tricks, and let's do something cutting edge.

00:07:22.279 --> 00:07:25.239
Let's make a linear model out of this data, right?

00:07:25.239 --> 00:07:28.119
We've gone through, we've cleaned this up, and we've created this model.

00:07:28.119 --> 00:07:33.440
The next step now is to present the results, and as an R user, there's a variety of different

00:07:33.440 --> 00:07:35.359
ways that I can do this.

00:07:35.359 --> 00:07:40.119
I can create a PowerPoint presentation, I can create an R Markdown document, maybe it's

00:07:40.119 --> 00:07:42.160
an email that I send.

00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:46.119
My tool of choice when I'm faced with this opportunity to communicate is to build a shiny

00:07:46.119 --> 00:07:51.480
application, and this allows me to build some sort of interactive web user interface that

00:07:51.480 --> 00:07:57.119
users can then access to touch and play with the model that I've developed, right?

00:07:57.119 --> 00:08:00.760
So I can publish this application to something like RStudio Connect, and then I can have

00:08:00.760 --> 00:08:05.119
my end users come in to the picture, and they're able to come in and interact with my model

00:08:05.119 --> 00:08:07.600
and get the insight that they need.

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:12.320
And now I'm in this happy place where I have a shiny application that's sitting on top

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:16.420
of all the work that I just did, and it's servicing all these end users, whether these

00:08:16.420 --> 00:08:21.279
are fellow analysts, business users, managers within my department, whatever the case is,

00:08:21.279 --> 00:08:26.760
they're able to come in, and in a very intuitive way, they can interact with my application,

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:30.279
they can interact with my model via this web application that I provided.

00:08:30.279 --> 00:08:33.239
Now I've been in this position before, and this is a great feeling to have, right?

00:08:33.239 --> 00:08:36.559
I've done all this hard work, and now people are using it, and it's getting recognition,

00:08:36.559 --> 00:08:41.679
and I'm helping people's, ideally I'm helping make people's lives better in some way.

00:08:41.679 --> 00:08:46.320
As this model starts to gain traction, and as this application starts to gain traction,

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:48.880
something always happens, or at least in my experience, something always happens, and

00:08:48.880 --> 00:08:53.479
that is another set of users slowly start to appear, and these users are a little bit

00:08:53.479 --> 00:08:58.320
different than the traditional user base, because they don't want a web application,

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:01.239
they want programmatic access to whatever I've done, right?

00:09:01.239 --> 00:09:05.479
They want to be able to access the underlying model, and typically it's at this point in

00:09:05.479 --> 00:09:10.400
the process where I start to scratch my head and say, well, we've had a good run, right?

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:12.080
Because I know this is what's coming.

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:15.239
I'm going to go to one of these engineers, and I'm going to get something like this in

00:09:15.239 --> 00:09:16.239
return.

00:09:16.239 --> 00:09:21.900
Now, this is not because R is bad, and Go is good, or vice versa, right?

00:09:21.900 --> 00:09:25.140
This is because these are different languages designed for different purposes, and I've

00:09:25.140 --> 00:09:30.260
been in many conversations with software engineers where they're trying so hard to understand

00:09:30.260 --> 00:09:35.179
my R code, and I'm trying so hard to explain it, but that handoff always has some amount

00:09:35.179 --> 00:09:37.219
of friction associated with it.

00:09:37.219 --> 00:09:40.539
And up until recently, that in my mind has just been kind of this necessary evil, right?

00:09:40.539 --> 00:09:44.780
At some point, my little baby R project has to grow up and enter the real world of software

00:09:44.780 --> 00:09:46.419
engineering.

00:09:46.419 --> 00:09:50.380
I propose today that there's actually a better solution, and that solution is to use Plumber

00:09:50.539 --> 00:09:52.739
as the intermediary here.

00:09:52.739 --> 00:09:56.979
Instead of going directly to building a Shiny application, I can instead expose my model

00:09:56.979 --> 00:10:01.460
or whatever it is that I've worked on as a Plumber API, and now I've given myself the

00:10:01.460 --> 00:10:05.659
flexibility to not only service end users who want programmatic access to the work that

00:10:05.659 --> 00:10:10.460
I've done, I can still continue to service my regular users, right?

00:10:10.460 --> 00:10:15.020
By using a Shiny application to access this API so that my traditional user base that

00:10:15.020 --> 00:10:18.859
are used to a web interface can continue to use the work that I've done.

00:10:18.859 --> 00:10:22.099
And at this point, now everybody's happy.

00:10:22.099 --> 00:10:23.099
So what does this look like?

00:10:23.099 --> 00:10:27.419
Let's take a short demo into RStudio.

00:10:27.419 --> 00:10:31.299
And so here we've got the RStudio IDE.

00:10:31.299 --> 00:10:33.140
This is a Plumber file that I have open.

00:10:33.140 --> 00:10:35.359
This is the one that we've been kind of looking at.

00:10:35.359 --> 00:10:38.219
And so I just want to walk through a few different things that are happening here, and then we'll

00:10:38.219 --> 00:10:41.380
run this and take a look at what happens under the hood.

00:10:41.380 --> 00:10:45.219
So I load the Plumber package, and then as I mentioned before, I have this model that

00:10:45.219 --> 00:10:46.219
I've saved out.

00:10:46.219 --> 00:10:49.979
So this is a very simplistic example, but the idea here is this could be a broad range

00:10:49.979 --> 00:10:50.979
of things, right?

00:10:50.979 --> 00:10:54.820
There was a great talk given earlier about serving Keras and TensorFlow models using

00:10:54.820 --> 00:10:55.820
Plumber, right?

00:10:55.820 --> 00:10:58.900
So it's really limitless in the scope of what you can do here.

00:10:58.900 --> 00:10:59.900
So I've loaded this model in.

00:10:59.900 --> 00:11:04.700
Again, I have this filter that logs some information about my incoming requests.

00:11:04.700 --> 00:11:09.340
And then finally, I have this endpoint that listens on this predict location in response

00:11:09.340 --> 00:11:11.320
to incoming post requests.

00:11:11.320 --> 00:11:15.059
And what this function does, if we look through this, it's actually fairly straightforward.

00:11:15.059 --> 00:11:20.419
It anticipates that the incoming request contains a post body object, and it anticipates

00:11:20.419 --> 00:11:23.219
that that post body object is JSON.

00:11:23.219 --> 00:11:26.059
And so it will try to parse that JSON into a native R data frame.

00:11:26.059 --> 00:11:28.500
If it can't, it returns an error to the user.

00:11:28.500 --> 00:11:34.159
Otherwise, it takes this new R data frame and sends it to my model to generate new predictions.

00:11:34.159 --> 00:11:38.059
Now one of the nice things about Plumber is that by default, any response that's generated

00:11:38.059 --> 00:11:43.380
within my endpoint function is automatically serialized into JSON, which is a language

00:11:43.380 --> 00:11:47.739
that most other computer programming languages or toolkits would be able to naturally ingest

00:11:47.739 --> 00:11:48.739
and understand.

00:11:48.739 --> 00:11:53.179
So once this prediction is made, down here with this predict call, the resulting predicted

00:11:53.179 --> 00:12:00.140
values will be returned as a JSON array to whichever client made this request.

00:12:00.140 --> 00:12:04.140
Now typically, when I've done something like this, and I've built several different APIs

00:12:04.140 --> 00:12:08.219
in this fashion, this is where Plumber previously has kind of been stretched to its limits in

00:12:08.219 --> 00:12:12.539
terms of what it can do from a documentation and an interactivity perspective.

00:12:12.700 --> 00:12:17.900
And that is because there's no way for me with these annotations to specify details

00:12:17.900 --> 00:12:20.219
about the request body itself.

00:12:20.219 --> 00:12:23.099
And so when I would run this, I would get the nice interface, and I would be able to

00:12:23.099 --> 00:12:26.859
click on my predict endpoint, but I would have no way to really interact with it.

00:12:26.859 --> 00:12:28.820
I would need some other tool chain, right?

00:12:28.820 --> 00:12:33.059
I could use curl from the command line, I could use postman or some other API client,

00:12:33.059 --> 00:12:36.940
but I needed some other tool to verify that things were working.

00:12:36.940 --> 00:12:41.619
However, like I mentioned earlier, with the newest updates in Plumber, I can now specify

00:12:41.619 --> 00:12:47.380
anything that I want about the API specification at runtime of my Plumber API.

00:12:47.380 --> 00:12:51.659
So here I have this, I'm loading the Plumber file, and then I'm using this run method.

00:12:51.659 --> 00:12:57.780
I've passed a function into Swagger, and here I'm defining what the request body to this

00:12:57.780 --> 00:13:00.500
predict endpoint should look like.

00:13:00.500 --> 00:13:03.979
And when I run this file, and I want to point out for just a moment that in the newest version

00:13:03.979 --> 00:13:08.820
of the RStudio IDE, there's some nice tooling built around Plumber, so I can automatically

00:13:08.820 --> 00:13:13.419
run the API from within the IDE with this run API button, and when I click on this,

00:13:13.419 --> 00:13:19.940
let me expand over here, I now have this nice user interface, just like I've come to expect,

00:13:19.940 --> 00:13:23.739
but the nice thing is, as I scroll down here, I can see my post endpoint.

00:13:23.739 --> 00:13:28.440
If I open this up, notice it says no parameters, which is fine, I didn't define any parameters,

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:31.820
but this is traditionally where it stopped, right, and I wanted some mechanism to test

00:13:31.820 --> 00:13:32.820
this out.

00:13:32.820 --> 00:13:37.260
Now, however, I see this request body, and it shows me not only an example of what this

00:13:37.260 --> 00:13:41.859
should look like, it shows me what the schema is, and then it gives me the opportunity to

00:13:41.859 --> 00:13:46.739
say, well, okay, this is what it looks like, let me try this out, and here's some values

00:13:46.739 --> 00:13:51.940
that are pre-populated by default, but I could come over, and I already have this pulled

00:13:51.940 --> 00:13:55.619
up, so I could come over and grab some JSON data.

00:13:55.619 --> 00:14:06.419
This is just a selection of the MT cars data in R, and I can come over here and edit this,

00:14:06.419 --> 00:14:14.299
paste it in, execute, and so a couple of things happen.

00:14:14.299 --> 00:14:16.960
Now we see the curl command that was generated here.

00:14:16.960 --> 00:14:20.859
We see the URL that I made this request to, so this is just running locally right now,

00:14:20.859 --> 00:14:24.940
and I've made a request to this predict endpoint, and then if I go down here, I see the response

00:14:24.940 --> 00:14:29.659
body, so this is the predicted value, the predicted miles per gallon value of this JSON

00:14:29.659 --> 00:14:34.260
data that I just passed into Plumber, and notice that I never left RStudio.

00:14:34.260 --> 00:14:38.940
I built this API, I tested this API, I verified that everything was working all from within

00:14:38.940 --> 00:14:41.179
RStudio.

00:14:41.179 --> 00:14:44.460
Now some of you at this point may be thinking, okay, that's great, right, this is all well

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:47.940
and good, James, but is the handoff really this easy, right?

00:14:47.940 --> 00:14:49.580
Is it really as easy as you made it seem?

00:14:49.580 --> 00:14:53.859
And I've had that question myself, and so I was actually on a phone call this past weekend

00:14:53.859 --> 00:14:57.900
with a close college friend of mine, and I was going through my talk and kind of telling

00:14:57.900 --> 00:15:01.419
him about what I was going to be demonstrating and everything like that, and he was following

00:15:01.419 --> 00:15:05.700
along, he's a mobile app developer, and at the end of the talk, he said, well, send me

00:15:05.700 --> 00:15:10.619
some information, or send me the GitHub repo to your API, and now this is an API that I've

00:15:10.619 --> 00:15:15.859
published to RStudio Connect, it's open, it's available, and so I sent him the repo, and

00:15:15.859 --> 00:15:19.460
I really didn't think anything of it, and a couple of days later, I got this in a text

00:15:19.460 --> 00:15:23.659
message.

00:15:23.659 --> 00:15:29.239
Now my friend knows how to spell R, and that's the end, right, he has no working knowledge

00:15:29.239 --> 00:15:33.679
of R, he's never interacted with R in any sort of context, yet here he's built an entire

00:15:33.679 --> 00:15:40.080
mobile app using Swift that's interacting with R built by somebody who doesn't know

00:15:40.080 --> 00:15:41.719
R.

00:15:41.719 --> 00:15:43.880
This is what Plumber enables us to do, right?

00:15:43.880 --> 00:15:48.780
We can now go straight from I have this idea in concept to I have this idea that anyone

00:15:48.780 --> 00:15:54.679
else can interact with, whether it's a shiny application or it's a mobile application,

00:15:54.679 --> 00:15:58.679
it's some sort of Java process, whatever the case is, I've now opened up the work that

00:15:58.679 --> 00:16:03.200
I'm doing to a much broader audience.

00:16:03.200 --> 00:16:06.919
If you'd like to take a look at some of the recent changes that have been made, they haven't

00:16:06.919 --> 00:16:11.640
quite made it to CRAN yet, but you can download the recent changes from GitHub, so you can

00:16:11.640 --> 00:16:17.440
do that in this manner, and then there are some additional resources that are available

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:21.440
in the Plumber documentation, as well as if you're curious about OpenAPI and what that

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:25.599
specification entails, and then the GitHub repository for this talk and the materials

00:16:25.599 --> 00:16:27.440
that I've used are here as well.

00:16:27.440 --> 00:16:28.440
Thank you very much.

00:16:28.440 --> 00:16:46.159
So we have some time for questions in here.

00:16:46.159 --> 00:16:47.880
Thank you.

00:16:47.880 --> 00:16:51.359
Is there anything on the roadmap for testing APIs?

00:16:51.359 --> 00:16:55.479
Right now what we're doing is we're opening the API in one R session and then running

00:16:55.479 --> 00:17:00.760
a script with our test calls to the endpoints that we've written in another.

00:17:00.760 --> 00:17:07.000
Will there be a certain more elegant way of doing that, either in the IDE or elsewhere?

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:08.280
Yeah.

00:17:08.280 --> 00:17:10.119
I've thought about that.

00:17:10.119 --> 00:17:13.900
There's nothing on the roadmap right now, primarily because since we've opened this

00:17:13.900 --> 00:17:20.599
up as, for lack of a better term, a REST API endpoint, there's lots of tooling that exists

00:17:20.599 --> 00:17:25.680
around testing those types of endpoints, and so we trust that users could leverage

00:17:25.680 --> 00:17:27.400
some of the existing tooling.

00:17:27.400 --> 00:17:31.439
At this point, I don't necessarily see a need for us to recreate something, but it's worth

00:17:31.439 --> 00:17:33.839
maybe continuing to think about.

00:17:33.839 --> 00:17:42.640
Is there, for validation of requests, something that you can kind of say, here are all the

00:17:42.640 --> 00:17:48.920
required parameters, without specifying inside the method, checking for things one by one?

00:17:48.920 --> 00:17:49.920
Yeah.

00:17:50.239 --> 00:17:53.839
That's where filters come in, and that kind of goes back to this broader idea of, well,

00:17:53.839 --> 00:17:57.319
sometimes I field questions about, is there integrated security, are there ways to verify

00:17:57.319 --> 00:17:58.920
things about the incoming requests?

00:17:58.920 --> 00:18:03.520
Right now there's not any sort of magic incantation that says, hey, verify this request or something

00:18:03.520 --> 00:18:04.520
like that.

00:18:04.520 --> 00:18:08.479
That's kind of up to me as the API developer or the R developer to say, maybe I define

00:18:08.479 --> 00:18:11.400
some filters that check for certain attributes.

00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:14.439
It might be something like a security token, or it might be something like I'm checking

00:18:14.439 --> 00:18:19.280
a timestamp to make sure that people aren't making requests beyond operating hours.

00:18:19.640 --> 00:18:23.040
So you have the flexibility to really define any criteria that you want, but we don't provide

00:18:23.040 --> 00:18:28.680
anything out of the box that provides verification or anything like that.

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:29.680
What's that?

00:18:29.680 --> 00:18:30.680
Okay.

00:18:30.680 --> 00:18:31.680
Great.

00:18:31.680 --> 00:18:35.880
Do you guys have any hubs of, like, lots of examples of Plumber APIs?

00:18:35.880 --> 00:18:41.760
Because I find it kind of hard sometimes to find examples and try to mimic them.

00:18:41.760 --> 00:18:42.760
Yeah.

00:18:42.760 --> 00:18:44.239
We are working on building out some resources.

00:18:44.239 --> 00:18:47.599
So the Plumber documentation and Plumber examples are something that we're working on building

00:18:47.640 --> 00:18:54.239
out, and we'll make sure that those are widely announced and publicized as they become available.

00:18:54.239 --> 00:18:55.239
And ETA.

00:18:55.239 --> 00:18:56.239
Sometime soon.

00:18:56.239 --> 00:18:59.719
But we're definitely, that's something that I'm trying to work on as well as building

00:18:59.719 --> 00:19:03.040
out some of these examples and everything like that.

00:19:03.040 --> 00:19:04.680
Two questions really quickly.

00:19:04.680 --> 00:19:11.760
First, can you specify a dependency, say, a proprietary dataset that you don't want

00:19:11.760 --> 00:19:13.680
to expose to the outside?

00:19:13.680 --> 00:19:16.959
And the second part is, where this background process is running?

00:19:17.040 --> 00:19:19.040
And do you have a control over it?

00:19:19.040 --> 00:19:20.040
Yeah.

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:21.040
Great question.

00:19:21.040 --> 00:19:22.560
So kind of two parts there.

00:19:22.560 --> 00:19:25.479
The first part is, can I specify something external?

00:19:25.479 --> 00:19:29.920
In the example that we just looked at, I actually had a serialized R object that I loaded from

00:19:29.920 --> 00:19:30.920
disk.

00:19:30.920 --> 00:19:34.280
So I loaded this model that I previously trained from disk, and then it was available to any

00:19:34.280 --> 00:19:37.199
process referenced within that API.

00:19:37.199 --> 00:19:40.520
So I could do that with a flat file or something like that.

00:19:40.520 --> 00:19:45.040
And then one of the nice advantages of publishing to something like RStudio Connect is those

00:19:45.119 --> 00:19:50.479
dependencies get identified and I can automatically send those files with my API source code.

00:19:50.479 --> 00:19:54.400
And then in terms of where the underlying process is running, in the example we just

00:19:54.400 --> 00:19:56.199
looked at, this was just running locally.

00:19:56.199 --> 00:20:01.079
As soon as I hit run API, it actually just spun up a small web server on my machine to

00:20:01.079 --> 00:20:02.640
surface this API.

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:06.400
When I publish it, there's a variety of ways you can deploy this thing.

00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:10.119
My recommendation is RStudio Connect because you have the click button deployment, but

00:20:10.119 --> 00:20:13.680
the plumber documentation runs through a variety of deployment options.

00:20:13.680 --> 00:20:15.239
Go ahead.

00:20:15.239 --> 00:20:22.239
I have a deployment related question.

00:20:22.239 --> 00:20:29.119
So I saw that RS Connect deploys today to the pro server, but not to anything else like

00:20:29.119 --> 00:20:30.119
DigitalOcean.

00:20:30.119 --> 00:20:36.719
Is that in the roadmap for you guys to include to make it easier to deploy to anything beyond

00:20:36.719 --> 00:20:38.719
just the pro server?

00:20:39.319 --> 00:20:46.239
As it stands right now, publishing from within the IDE, just as kind of a reference, I meant

00:20:46.239 --> 00:20:48.520
to showcase this.

00:20:48.520 --> 00:20:53.280
From within the IDE, we mentioned that I have access to run API up here.

00:20:53.280 --> 00:20:57.839
I also have access to this publish button where I can publish this to RStudio Connect.

00:20:57.839 --> 00:21:01.800
That's where that interaction ends.

00:21:01.800 --> 00:21:04.920
But again, in the documentation for Plumber, there's some guidelines around if you wanted

00:21:04.920 --> 00:21:08.400
to publish to maybe DigitalOcean, for example, there's some guidelines around how you might

00:21:08.400 --> 00:21:09.400
do that.

00:21:09.400 --> 00:21:22.560
But I don't anticipate integration of that type of workflow into the IDE.

00:21:22.560 --> 00:21:25.160
Just a quick question with the new improvements.

00:21:25.160 --> 00:21:28.520
You showed two different files you were working on with the OpenAPI.

00:21:28.520 --> 00:21:34.079
Is that the same one coded differently with the new improvements with OpenAPI or are those

00:21:34.079 --> 00:21:41.359
two files, I mean, is it the same thing, I guess?

00:21:41.359 --> 00:21:42.359
Yeah.

00:21:42.359 --> 00:21:44.479
So there's two different files that are at play here.

00:21:44.479 --> 00:21:47.959
One is the Plumber file and this defines all of the R logic.

00:21:47.959 --> 00:21:52.040
Plumber also has this concept of an entry point file, which if Plumber, when I run an

00:21:52.040 --> 00:21:58.560
API that's a Plumber API, it will look for an entry point.R file within that same folder,

00:21:58.560 --> 00:21:59.560
within that same directory.

00:21:59.560 --> 00:22:03.439
And if it finds it, it will use that to find additional details about the API.

00:22:03.800 --> 00:22:06.079
So here, I could programmatically alter my API.

00:22:06.079 --> 00:22:10.640
I could add additional routers, but what I'm doing in this case is I'm just simply updating

00:22:10.640 --> 00:22:15.560
the specification file with this named list that will then get parsed into JSON and rendered

00:22:15.560 --> 00:22:17.560
the way that we saw it.

00:22:17.560 --> 00:22:18.560
Awesome.

00:22:18.560 --> 00:22:24.560
Well, do you have one more question?

00:22:24.560 --> 00:22:28.640
Yeah, I'll do one more.

00:22:28.640 --> 00:22:37.079
If you can say a few words regarding scaling, I mean, how many posts can this support?

00:22:37.079 --> 00:22:38.599
Can this scale up?

00:22:38.599 --> 00:22:40.680
Yeah, that's the classic question, right?

00:22:40.680 --> 00:22:41.780
Does R scale?

00:22:41.780 --> 00:22:43.599
And the answer is yes, absolutely.

00:22:43.599 --> 00:22:47.640
And it really depends on the way in which you choose to deploy this.

00:22:47.640 --> 00:22:51.119
If you deploy this to RStudio Connect, you can actually go in and adjust the number of

00:22:51.119 --> 00:22:54.439
processes that are dedicated to the support of that API.

00:22:54.439 --> 00:22:57.959
So the notion here, and part of the underlying question I think is, well, I know that R is

00:22:58.280 --> 00:22:59.280
single-threaded.

00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:03.479
If I'm running R in the back end of my API, I anticipate that there may be challenges

00:23:03.479 --> 00:23:04.479
with scalability.

00:23:04.479 --> 00:23:10.040
RStudio Connect provides a solution to that by allowing you to spin up concurrent R processes

00:23:10.040 --> 00:23:11.079
that support your API.

00:23:11.079 --> 00:23:16.040
So essentially, you add this notion of multi-threadedness to your R process.

00:23:16.040 --> 00:23:19.280
And then there's, again, depending on the way in which you choose to deploy this, you

00:23:19.280 --> 00:23:23.119
could deploy this in an environment where it maybe at auto scales in some sort of a

00:23:23.119 --> 00:23:24.839
Docker cluster or something like that.

00:23:24.839 --> 00:23:27.560
So it's really up to you in terms of how do you want to deploy this thing, but it certainly

00:23:27.560 --> 00:23:31.199
is able to scale and meet a high load of demand.

00:23:31.199 --> 00:23:35.959
I know that in the talk I was in earlier where they were discussing using this at T-Mobile,

00:23:35.959 --> 00:23:41.520
they mentioned serving a very, very large customer base and their mobile app interfaces

00:23:41.520 --> 00:23:47.079
using Plumber and accessing R APIs that way, and they've had no issues with it.

00:23:47.079 --> 00:23:47.959
Thank you all again very much.

